Each of the other white skeletons lay on the graves that had once encased them. Each lay with its arm bones crossed over its ribs. Water shone in the grass. A bird twittered somewhere in the forest.

Rafe frowned at him and glanced at Matthis's arms, which had turned gray from fingertip to above the elbows. Matthis rubbed his wrists, which had become stiff. Rafe clicked his tongue. 

The mob had shrunk. Knives lay forgotten on the ground. A few more turned and walked toward the village and didn't look back. Mercy's eyes bulged, and she bared her teeth at Matthis. She reminded him of a bear he saw once.

Matthis's bones felt turned to dust as well. He failed to stand twice. Once again, something felt ripped from him. With one hand on Kendrick's old headstone, he pushed himself up. Maud remained by Kendrick's grave, her hands curled in her lap. Matthis limped to the nearest grave, its late occupant folded in repose upon it. The black skeleton and two white skeletons that had remained on their feet didn't move. Their heads did not turn. They stood at attention and stared at nothing. Matthis ignored Rafe and Mercy and everything else. He knelt by the next skeleton and laid his hands on it. 

Each time he repeated whatever he had done with Kendrick to another skeleton, the bones faded into dust the way light faded from a dying lamp. When the last of the skeletons that lay upon their graves puffed into dust and sparkled in the sunlight, his veins stood black on his arms, hard as sundried worms, from finger to elbow. His nail beds had turned black at some point.

Rafe stood nearby, his face hard. Matthis saw Mercy, who stood with three others. The rest had left. She looked feral. She had kneaded a hole in her apron. Her eyes had turned bloodshot. Spittle trickled down one corner of her mouth.

The white-robed man stood beside her, arms folded, face expressionless. He had dismounted his horse, which stood at attention nearby. A balding little man behind him hunched over a clay writing tablet, smudging things out, scratching things in, muttering to himself.

Rafe leaned over and pulled Matthis to his feet. "Was it worth it?" he hissed. "Please tell me it was worth it."

Matthis ignored him. 

"Monster," whispered Mercy. She whipped around and marched back down the hill.

Matthis's knees buckled. He sagged into the grass. The black skeleton and two white skeletons stood over him. A line from Matthis's chest connected him to two of them. 

Feet appeared in Matthis's vision. He tried to lift his head to look at them. Instead, drool spilled out of his mouth and on his trousers. He tried to wipe it. His hands felt too large and thick. They were both black. 

"You have violated all the Tenets of Magic," snapped the little balding man. What remained of his hair hung in a shiny gray sheet around his neck. "And thus, you have suffered the effects of its improper use. You're lucky the unguided magic didn't combust."

Matthis angled himself to look at the little man and his robed companion. The little man had a straight back, perfect angles in his jacket, no dust. The robed man breathed deeply as he watched. Rafe stood nearby, fists clenched, jaw tight, eyes aflame. 

"Mining wizards," said the little man, "are barred from the use of magic outside the Tenets. You have grievously violated the laws of magic." The man had shrunken eyes like a mole's. Ink stains splotched his fingertips, but not a fleck touched his sleeves. "You will be sanctioned for this by the Miner's Guild, rogue wizard."

The robed man said nothing. He watched the skeletons, which stared at nothing. He looked at Rafe, who was shaking, face red. The black skeleton moaned. The robed man looked from Matthis to Rafe. 

"It's appalling to see this kind of magic use by wizards or sorcerers of any kind." The little man was spitting. Flecks flew from his mouth and spread everywhere. "How dare a wizard abuse his power in such a --"

"He is not a wizard, Pellin."

The little man shrank into the robed man's shadow. His beady eyes glared at Matthis. He pulled his dry lips from his crooked teeth. "The Miner's Guild has no registered sorcerers. And if they did, no magic user is sanctioned to violate the Tenets of Magic under any --"

"You're here from the Collegium," said Rafe, his voice even, but low and dangerous, "to regulate the use of magic?"

" -- which places your guild in an extremely terrible position -- "

"Yes," said the robed man. He surveyed Rafe. Rafe stared back, face red. A vein pulsed on his neck. The white robed man raised a brow and said nothing. He held Rafe's fiery eyes for a moment. Then he turned back to his horse and took it by the reins. He frowned at Matthis and walked his horse down the hill. The little balding man followed, still muttering to himself. 

Matthis's ear itched. When he drew back his hand from it, blood spotted his fingers. Interesting, he thought. The hill had turned fuzzy before he realized. 

He spotted a black line between him and the black skeleton. He tried to stand but failed to move his legs. Something in him lurched. He wanted to face the black skeleton. He felt a tug from the black line. The black skeleton moved into his vision and knelt in front of Matthis. Their knees touched. Matthis cocked his head. So did the skeleton. 

"What do you want?" Matthis's words sounded fuzzy. 

The skeleton did nothing. Matthis reached out to touch the line that connected them. His hand passed through it. His arm went limp and fell onto his leg. Matthis panted. 

"Show me what you want."

The skeleton didn't move for a moment. Light glinted from its black skull. Wind slipped through the grass. Either focused or deaf, Matthis could hear nothing. The edges of his vision darkened. He saw only the skeleton. 

The skeleton lifted a black hand, palm toward Matthis, fingers up. 

Matthis couldn't think. He raised his hand and placed his palm against the skeleton's. Something ripped from him. The black line vanished. Matthis coughed. Blood spattered the skeleton's skull and teeth. Nearby, Rafe cursed. 

"You're free," said Matthis. 

And he slumped to the side. Blood trickled from his ear and down his senseless neck. Insects clicked and buzzed in the sunlight. Rafe rushed to Matthis's side, which rose and fell in long, deep breaths. 

The skeleton leaned forward and held Matthis's hand. 